%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%    SEC. 2  Definition               %%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Definition}

\subsection{Basic Ingredients}
Let us represent the Weyl fermion $\psi_Calpha,{\bar \psi}_{\dot Calpha}$
(2 complex components, $Calpha,{\dot Calpha}=1,2,$ ) 
and their 'suffixes-raised' partners as in Fig.1.
Raising and lowering the spinor suffixes is done by
the antisymmetric tensors $\epsilon^{\alpha\beta}, \epsilon_{{\alpha\beta}}$:\ 
%*** def1%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{eqnarray}
\psi^Calpha=\epsilon^{\alpha\beta}\psi_Pbeta{\quad ,}\quad
{\bar \psi}^{\dot Calpha}=\epsilon^{{\dot Calpha}{\dot Pbeta}}{\bar \psi}_{\dot Pbeta}{\quad ,}\quad
\epsilon^{12}=\epsilon_{21}=1{\quad ,}
\label{def1}
\end{eqnarray}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
where $\epsilon^{\alpha\beta}$ and $\epsilon_{\alpha\beta}$ are in the inverse relation:\ 
$\epsilon^{\alpha\beta}\epsilon_{Pbeta
